[1] Paraguay
Date: 23 Feb 2007
From: Joseph Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Playfuls.com [edited]
<http://www.playfuls.com/news_004954_Dengue_Fever_Epidemic_Ravages_Paraguay_Over_10000_People_Ill.html>

A dengue fever epidemic is ravaging Paraguay, where more than 10 000
people have fallen ill.
The newspaper ABC-Color Friday [23 Feb 2007] reported 650 new cases
of the illness, which produces symptoms including bad headaches, high
fever, diarrhea, vomiting and severe joint pain.
At least 4 people have died from the virus, against which there is no
vaccine or medication.
The Paraguayan Congress is poised to declare a 60-day state of
emergency that will allow it to adopt measures to combat the epidemic.
A bill to establish the state of emergency has been approved
unanimously by the lower house of the legislature, and the Senate is
scheduled to debate it on Monday [26 Feb 2007].
In the meantime, critics ... claim that deficient sanitation and
open-air garbage dumps have provided ideal conditions for the insects
that transmit the virus to reproduce.
Unofficial estimates [of dengue cases are] as high as 60 000.
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
Chief Scientist,
Biosecurity and Biosurveillance
EAI Corporation
<jdudley@eaicorp.com>
[ProMED requests information about the numbers of dengue and DHF
cases that have occurred so far in this epidemic and the progress
being made to eliminate the breeding sites of the mosquito vector,
_Aedes aegypti_. If the unofficial figure cited above is correct, the
Paraguay health authorities have an immense job ahead of them to
bring the epidemic under control. The report posted in the last
Dengue DHF update on 19 Feb 2007 (archive no. 20070219.0630) from the
Pan American Health Organization jointly with the Paraguay Ministry
of Health indicated that a vigorous campaign was being launched to
control the disease. ProMED thanks A-Lan Banks for an earlier report
of dengue in Paraguay.
A map of Paraguay can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/paraguay_pol98.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]
